  "sections": [
    {
      "type": "grammarIntro",
      "title": "Saying What Something Is",
      "icon": "📐",
      "summary": "です and だ are the Japanese words for 'is', 'am', and 'are'. They close nearly every descriptive sentence.",
      "whyItMatters": "Every Japanese sentence that describes what something or someone is uses です or だ. Mastering all their forms unlocks a huge range of everyday expressions.",
      "youWillLearn": [
        "The core pattern: X は Y です",
        "All polite forms: です / でした / ではありません / ではありませんでした",
        "All plain (informal) forms: だ / だった / ではない / ではなかった",
        "Short-form negatives: じゃありません and じゃない",
        "When to use polite speech vs plain speech"
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "grammarRule",
      "id": "rule_desu_pattern",
      "pattern": [
        {
          "label": "TOPIC",
          "color": "topic",
          "text": "X"
        },
        {
          "label": "PARTICLE",
          "color": "connector",
          "text": "は"
        },
        {
          "label": "PREDICATE",
          "color": "predicate",
          "text": "Y"
        },
        {
          "label": "COPULA",
          "color": "verb",
          "text": "です"
        }
      ],
      "meaning": "'X is Y' (polite)",
      "explanation": "は marks the topic — what you are talking about. Y is the predicate — what you say about it. です closes the sentence politely, equivalent to English 'is', 'am', or 'are'.",
      "notes": [
        "は is written with the hiragana は (ha) but pronounced 'wa' as a particle.",
        "Add か to the end to form a yes/no question: 先生ですか？ (Are you a teacher?)",
        "です follows nouns and な-adjectives directly. For い-adjectives, add です to the plain form as-is: やさしいです."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "わたし",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "I"
            },
            {
              "text": "は",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "先生",
              "role": "predicate",
              "gloss": "teacher"
            },
            {
              "text": "です",
              "role": "verb"
            }
          ],
          "en": "I am a teacher.",
          "breakdown": "Topic: 'I' → Predicate: 'am a teacher'"
        },
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "父",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "my father"
            },
            {
              "text": "は",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "やさしい",
              "role": "modifier",
              "gloss": "kind"
            },
            {
              "text": "人",
              "role": "predicate",
              "gloss": "person"
            },
            {
              "text": "です",
              "role": "verb"
            }
          ],
          "en": "My father is a kind person.",
          "breakdown": "Topic: 'my father' → Predicate: 'is a kind person'"
        },
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "あの人",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "that person"
            },
            {
              "text": "は",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "先生",
              "role": "predicate",
              "gloss": "teacher"
            },
            {
              "text": "ですか",
              "role": "verb"
            }
          ],
          "en": "Is that person a teacher?",
          "breakdown": "Adding か turns the statement into a yes/no question"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "grammarRule",
      "id": "rule_da_casual",
      "pattern": [
        {
          "label": "TOPIC",
          "color": "topic",
          "text": "X"
        },
        {
          "label": "PARTICLE",
          "color": "connector",
          "text": "は"
        },
        {
          "label": "PREDICATE",
          "color": "predicate",
          "text": "Y"
        },
        {
          "label": "COPULA",
          "color": "verb",
          "text": "だ"
        }
      ],
      "meaning": "'X is Y' (plain / casual)",
      "explanation": "だ is the plain (informal) equivalent of です. Use it in casual speech with close friends or family. Do NOT use だ after い-adjectives — in plain speech, い-adjectives stand alone without any copula. Only nouns and な-adjectives take だ.",
      "notes": [
        "だ follows nouns and な-adjectives directly: 先生だ (is a teacher).",
        "い-adjectives do NOT take だ in plain speech. Say うれしい — not うれしいだ. The い ending already signals the plain form.",
        "Using だ with a superior or in a formal setting sounds abrupt or rude — use です in those contexts.",
        "よ and ね attach after だ in casual speech: 先生だよ (it's a teacher!), 先生だね (a teacher, right?)."
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "わたし",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "I"
            },
            {
              "text": "は",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "先生",
              "role": "predicate",
              "gloss": "teacher"
            },
            {
              "text": "だ",
              "role": "verb"
            }
          ],
          "en": "I'm a teacher. (casual)",
          "breakdown": "Same meaning as わたしは先生です — plain register for casual situations"
        },
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "あの人",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "that person"
            },
            {
              "text": "は",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "友だち",
              "role": "predicate",
              "gloss": "friend"
            },
            {
              "text": "だ",
              "role": "verb"
            },
            {
              "text": "よ",
              "role": "particle"
            }
          ],
          "en": "That person is a friend, you know. (casual assertion)",
          "breakdown": "だ + よ adds a gentle 'you know' feeling — common in casual speech"
        },
        {
          "parts": [
            {
              "text": "父",
              "role": "topic",
              "gloss": "my father"
            },
            {
              "text": "は",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "先生",
              "role": "predicate",
              "gloss": "teacher"
            },
            {
              "text": "では",
              "role": "particle"
            },
            {
              "text": "ない",
              "role": "verb"
            }
          ],
          "en": "My father is not a teacher. (plain negative)",
          "breakdown": "ではない is the plain negative — polite equivalent is ではありません"
        }
      ]
